quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Creating a Class[/h1]

Let's create a class with one public method, and have it print out "Hi". [code format="cpp" ][b]class [/b]BankAccount {
  [b]public[/b]:
    void sayHi() {
      cout << "Hi" << endl;
    }
};[/code]
The next step is to instantiate an object of our [b]BankAccount [/b]class, in the same way we define variables of a type, the difference being that our object's type will be [b]BankAccount[/b].[code format="cpp" codeId="252"]int main() 
{
  [b]BankAccount [/b]test;
  test.[b]sayHi()[/b];
}[/code]
Our object named [b]test [/b]has all the members of the class defined. 
Notice the [b]dot separator (.)[/b] that is used to access and call the method of the object.
[note]We must declare a class [b]before [/b]using it, as we do with functions.[/note]
